Who can help lamenting, that so rational a cause should be rested upon reasons, so much 
fitter to beget objections, than to remove them? 

But with men who are unanimous and hearty about measures, nothing so weak but may 
pass in the character of a reason : nor is this the first instance in the world, where the con- 
clusion has supported the premises, instead of the premisee the conclusion. 



